<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FFDFFF95A7ADFE58FCC4DF86" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0755A263FFDFFF95A7ADFE58FEF0DDD0" blockId="70.[189,310,439,465]" box="[189,310,439,465]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<heading id="5C1D150FFFDFFF95A7ADFE58FEF0DDD0" bold="true" box="[189,310,439,465]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFDFFF95A7ADFE58FEF0DDD0" bold="true" box="[189,310,439,465]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FFDFFF95A7ADFE09FCC4DF86" blockId="70.[188,1406,486,904]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Based on the original description, supplemented by observations of 
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FFDFFF95A4F6FE09FB6EDE01" author="Quintero D. J." box="[998,1192,486,512]" firstAuthor="Quintero" journalOrPublisher="Studies on the Fauna of Curacao &amp; other Caribbean Islands" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 54" part="65" refId="ref152409" refString="Quintero D. J. 1983. Revision of the amblypygid spiders of Cuba and their relationships with the Caribbean and continental American amblypygid fauna. Studies on the Fauna of Curacao &amp; other Caribbean Islands 65: 1 - 54." title="Revision of the amblypygid spiders of Cuba and their relationships with the Caribbean and continental American amblypygid fauna" type="journal article" year="1983">Quintero (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, this species may be separated from other 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FFDFFF95A6CCFDE5FD8FDE25" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1892" box="[476,585,522,548]" class="Arachnida" family="Charinidae" genus="Charinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFDFFF95A6CCFDE5FD8FDE25" box="[476,585,522,548]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Charinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Amazonia and northern South America by means of the following combination of characters: median eyes and median ocular tubercle absent; lateral eyes reduced; sternum with undivided platelets, not pairs; pedipalp femur with three dorsal spines and three or four ventral spines; pedipalp patella with three dorsal spines and large setiferous tubercle between spine I and distal margin, and two prominent setiferous tubercles, decreasing in size, proximal to spine III; pedipalp patella with two ventral spines; pedipalp tibia with two dorsal spines, distal spine very long, more than half length of tibia, proximal spine one-third length of distal spine; cheliceral claw with five or six teeth; pedipalp tarsus with two dorsal spines; tibia of leg I with 23 articles, and with 41 articles; leg IV basitibia with three articles (
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FFDFFF95A6B0FCC9FD88DF40" author="Ravelo P. O." box="[416,590,806,833]" firstAuthor="Ravelo" journalOrPublisher="Boletin de la Sociedad Venezolana de Espeleologia" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="77 - 85" part="6" refId="ref152816" refString="Ravelo P. O. 1975. Speleophrynus tronchonii, nuevo genero y especie de amblipigios de la familia Charontidae, en una cueva de Venezuela. Boletin de la Sociedad Venezolana de Espeleologia 6: 77 - 85." title="Speleophrynus tronchonii, nuevo genero y especie de amblipigios de la familia Charontidae" type="journal article" volumeTitle="una cueva de Venezuela" year="1975">Ravelo (1975)</bibRefCitation>
, and also 
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FFDFFF95A5D6FCC9FC41DF40" author="Quintero D. J." box="[710,903,806,833]" firstAuthor="Quintero" journalOrPublisher="Studies on the Fauna of Curacao &amp; other Caribbean Islands" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 54" part="65" refId="ref152409" refString="Quintero D. J. 1983. Revision of the amblypygid spiders of Cuba and their relationships with the Caribbean and continental American amblypygid fauna. Studies on the Fauna of Curacao &amp; other Caribbean Islands 65: 1 - 54." title="Revision of the amblypygid spiders of Cuba and their relationships with the Caribbean and continental American amblypygid fauna" type="journal article" year="1983">Quintero (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, considered the distitibia to be part of the tibia, resulting in a count of four articles); leg IV distitibia trichobothrium 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFDFFF95A338FCA5FB82DF65" box="[1064,1092,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">bc</emphasis>
situated closer to 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFDFFF95A20AFCA5FAFADF65" box="[1306,1340,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">sbf</emphasis>
than to 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFDFFF95A7CBFC82FF34DF86" box="[219,242,877,903]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">bf</emphasis>
; 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFDFFF95A611FC81FEDFDF86" box="[257,281,878,903]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">sc</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFDFFF95A643FC82FEA1DF86" box="[339,359,877,903]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">sf</emphasis>
series each with five trichobothria.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FFDFFF95A7ADFC40FCBDDFF9" box="[189,891,943,1016]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0755A263FFDFFF95A7ADFC40FE82DFC8" blockId="70.[189,324,943,969]" box="[189,324,943,969]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<heading id="5C1D150FFFDFFF95A7ADFC40FE82DFC8" bold="true" box="[189,324,943,969]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFDFFF95A7ADFC40FE82DFC8" bold="true" box="[189,324,943,969]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FFDFFF95A7ADFC31FCBDDFF9" blockId="70.[189,891,989,1016]" box="[189,891,989,1016]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Patronym honoring Juan Antonio Tronchoni (
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FFDFFF95A5C3FC32FCA8DFF9" author="Ravelo P. O." box="[723,878,989,1016]" firstAuthor="Ravelo" journalOrPublisher="Boletin de la Sociedad Venezolana de Espeleologia" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="77 - 85" part="6" refId="ref152816" refString="Ravelo P. O. 1975. Speleophrynus tronchonii, nuevo genero y especie de amblipigios de la familia Charontidae, en una cueva de Venezuela. Boletin de la Sociedad Venezolana de Espeleologia 6: 77 - 85." title="Speleophrynus tronchonii, nuevo genero y especie de amblipigios de la familia Charontidae" type="journal article" volumeTitle="una cueva de Venezuela" year="1975">Ravelo 1975</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
